<DOC><DOCNO> AP890706-0073 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-06-89 1031EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0506thunderstorm.Tonight...Cloudyandhumidwithchanceofshowers.Lowinth</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0506,0741</SECOND><HEAD>Rain Drenches East Coast for a Second Day</HEAD><HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with third person missing in Delaware,rain records in N.J., Georgia storm stranding motorists; PICKS UP 12thgraf pvs, `Near Alexandria ...'</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Heavy rain continued for a second day today on the alreadysaturated East Coast, and flash flood watches were posted in sevenstates.   Thunderstorms produced large hail and strong winds in Minnesotalate Wednesday. Winds gusted to 62 mph at International Falls andblew over vehicles and downed trees at Pelican Lake. The stormsweakened early today.   The rains in the Northeast were remnants of Tropical StormAllison, which came ashore last week and dumped up to 20 inches ofrain in Texas and Louisiana.   Wednesday's storms were blamed for at least two deaths.   Scattered showers and thunderstorms extended from Florida and thecentral Gulf Coast to New England early today, with rain mostprevalent from central Virginia to coastal New England.   Flash flood watches were in effect in North Carolina, Virginia,West Virginia, Maryland, Pennsylvania, New Jersey and New York.   Two people drowned and a third person was missing today inDelaware, where up to 10 inches of rain drenched the state. Morethan 450 people were forced to evacuate their homes. Rainfallamounts included 9.52 inches at Claymont and 6.63 at Wilmington, thehighest 24-hour total for any July day in 95 years of recordkeeping.   Rainfall records also were broken throughout New Jersey,including Newark, which logged 2.45 inches of rain.   Rain washed out track beds and reduced Amtrak service betweenWashington and New York City to one track. The hardest hit area wasbetween Wilmington and Philadelphia, where rain fell at up to 3inches an hour, said Amtrak spokeswoman Cliff Black.   In Philadelphia, three workers were injured at the Naval Shipyardwhen a tarpaulin tore open and sent them plunging 40 feet to thedeck of an aircraft carrier, a shipyard spokesman said. The threewere bailing rainwater out of the tarp.   A driving thunderstorm stranded hundreds of motorists in CobbCounty, Ga., overturning mobile homes and flooding streets. Policetoday said crews worked past midnight to free the drivers, hoursafter the rain ended.   Near Alexandria, La., 56 residents in Rapides Parish wereevacuated by Wednesday night as officials warned of backwaterflooding.   A few showers dampened western New Mexico and southeasternArizona today.   Record high temperatures for the date Wednesday were set inWyoming, North Dakota, Nebraska, Florida and Colorado, where atleast seven communities broke the 100-degree mark.   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms fromnorthern Minnesota across northern Wisconsin to upper Michigan;along the East Coast from southern and central New England acrossmuch of New York state through Florida; and over Alabama andMississippi and much of Louisiana, Tennessee, Kentucky and WestVirginia.   Predicted highs: in the upper 80s and in the low 90s fromnorthern New England across the lower Great Lakes, from the SouthCarolina coast across Florida, over the lower Mississippi Valley,northern Minnesota and the upper Missouri Valley; in the 90s overthe remainder of the Mississippi Valley, the remainder of thePlains, from southern Montana across New Mexico, over the GreatBasin and the central Pacific Coast; 100 degrees and higher fromwestern Montana across Utah and central California: from 115 to 120over the Desert Southwest; and in the 80s over much of the rest ofthe nation.   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 49 degrees at YellowstonePark, Wyo., to 96 degrees at Phoenix.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 74 foggy; Boston 65 rain; Buffalo 67 fair;Charleston, S.C., 78 fair; Cincinnati 71 fair; Cleveland 68 fair;Miami 74 fair; New York 69 foggy; Philadelphia 70 drizzle;Pittsburgh 67 foggy; Portland, Maine, 65 rain; Washington 73 showers.   _Central: Bismarck 72 fair; Chicago 74 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 77fair; Denver 71 fair; Des Moines 68 fair; Indianapolis 73 hazy;Kansas City 72 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 77 fair; Nashville 71foggy; New Orleans 76 foggy; St. Louis 77 fair.   _West: Albuquerque 77 fair; Anchorage 52 partly cloudy; Las Vegas87 fair; Los Angeles 65 foggy; Phoenix 93 fair; Salt Lake City 67fair; San Diego 64 foggy; San Francisco 55 fair; Seattle 58 fair.   _Canada: Montreal 66 fair; Toronto 63 fair.</TEXT></DOC>